#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:359
msgid "Disabling ``malloc``/``free`` Stack Traces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:361
msgid ""
"In a program that uses ``malloc``/``free`` (or their C++ equivalent, "
"``operator new``/``operator delete``) very frequently, taking a stack trace "
"at all invocations to ``malloc``/``free`` can be very expensive. As a "
"result, if you find your program to be very slow when using ASan, you can "
"try using the option ``malloc_context_size=0``, like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:371
msgid ""
"This prevents ASan from reporting the location of memory leaks or offering "
"insight into where the memory for a heap-based memory error originated, but "
"may provide tremendous speed ups."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:376
msgid "Comparison to ``SAFE_HEAP``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:378
msgid ""
"Emscripten provides a ``SAFE_HEAP`` mode, which can be activated by running "
"``emcc`` with ``-sSAFE_HEAP``. This does several things, some of which "
"overlap with sanitizers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:382
msgid ""
"In general, ``SAFE_HEAP`` focuses on the specific pain points that come up "
"when targeting Wasm. The sanitizers on the other hand focus on the specific "
"pain points that are involved with using languages like C/C++. Those two "
"sets overlap, but are not identical. Which you should use depends on which "
"types of problems you are looking for. You may want to test with all "
"sanitizers and with ``SAFE_HEAP`` for maximal coverage, but you may need to "
"build separately for each mode, since not all sanitizers are compatible with "
"each other, and not all of them are compatible with ``SAFE_HEAP`` (because "
"the sanitizers do some pretty radical things!). You will get a compiler "
"error if there is an issue with the flags you passed. A reasonable set of "
"separate test builds to do might be: ASan, UBsan, and ``SAFE_HEAP``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:394
msgid "The specific things ``SAFE_HEAP`` errors on include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:396
msgid ""
"**NULL pointer (address 0) reads or writes**. As mentioned earlier, this is "
"annoying in WebAssembly and JavaScript because 0 is just a normal address, "
"so you don't get an immediate segfault, which can be confusing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:399
msgid ""
"**Unaligned reads or writes**. These work in WebAssembly, but on some "
"platforms an incorrectly-aligned read or write may be much slower, and with "
"wasm2js (``WASM=0``) it will be incorrect, as JavaScript Typed Arrays do not "
"allow unaligned operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:403
msgid ""
"**Reads or writes past the top of valid memory** as managed by ``sbrk()``, "
"that is, memory that was not properly allocated by ``malloc()``. This is not "
"specific to Wasm, however, in JavaScript if the address is big enough to be "
"outside the Typed Array, ``undefined`` is returned which can be very "
"confusing, which is why this was added (in Wasm at least an error is thrown; "
"``SAFE_HEAP`` still helps with Wasm though, by checking the area between the "
"top of ``sbrk()``'s memory and the end of the Wasm Memory)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:411
msgid ""
"``SAFE_HEAP`` does these checks by instrumenting every single load and "
"store. That has the cost of slowing things down, but it does give a simple "
"guarantee of finding *all* such problems. It can also be done after "
"compilation, on an arbitrary Wasm binary, while the sanitizers must be done "
"when compiling from source."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:417
msgid ""
"In comparison, UBSan can also find null pointer reads and writes. It does "
"not instrument every single load and store, however, as it is done during "
"compilation of the source code, so the checks are added where clang knows "
"they are needed. This is much more efficient, but there is a risk of codegen "
"and optimizations changing something, or clang missing a specific location."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/debugging/Sanitizers.rst:423
msgid ""
"ASan can find reads or writes of unallocated memory, which includes "
"addresses above the ``sbrk()``-managed memory. It may be more efficient than "
"``SAFE_HEAP`` in some cases: while it also checks every load and store, the "
"LLVM optimizer is run after it adds those checks, which can remove some of "
"them."
msgstr ""
